<figureCitation id="99E80DE0FF913949E9CEC1F7FC7F5DE8" box="[767,896,1732,1758]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[227,270,1754,1780]" captionTargetBox="[227,1437,675,1723]" captionTargetId="figure-233@64.[227,1437,675,1723]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 22. Fish otoliths from the US middle and upper Eocene. A–C. “Atherina” debilis (Koken, 1888). A. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 6 from bed U, Texas (IRSNB P 10122). B–C. Moodys Branch F., Jackson, Riverside Park, Mississippi (IRSNB P 10123–10124). D–E. Mene garviei sp. nov., Landrum M., Pin Oak Creek, Texas. D. Holotype (IRSNB P 10125). E. Paratype (IRSNB P 10126). F–G. Psettodes trapeziformis Müller, 1999, Piney Point F., Virginia. F. Pamunkey River, 1 km E of Eanes property (IRSNB P 10127). G. Pamunkey River, Devil’s Hole (IRSNB P 10128). H–I. Carangidae indet. H. Wheelock M., Little Brazos River, Stenzel loc., Texas (IRSNB P 10129). I. “Stone City beds”, Stone City Bluff, Brazos River, sample 2 from bed P, Texas (IRSNB P 10130). 1 = ventral view; 2 = inner view; 3 = anterior view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6484401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6484401/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 22H–I</figureCitation>
